  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: Many countries in Southeast Asia serve roti prata, a flatbread dish with
    Indian influences. In Malaysia, this street food dish is called roti canai, while
    in South India, it is called parotta. The dough for roti prata is made with wheat
    flour and is stretched out onto a flat grill pan into a large, thin sheet. A
    multiple layer is created by folding the edges inward. In order to have it crispy
    and gently browned, fry the roti prata for three to five minutes. Even though
    roti prata is typically served with a curry dipping sauce made with either meat
    or vegetables, it can be eaten on its own. Additionally, it can be prepared with
    a variety of components, including eggs, cheese, onions, chocolate, and mushrooms.
    Though it can be eaten as a snack at any time of day, roti prata, which is frequently
    found in hawker centers, is a popular breakfast dish in Singapore.
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
